### File Descriptions
```
- app.py
  The main backend Python file implementing the entire web application using a web framework like Flask.
  It handles routing for all eight pages, reads and writes data to the local text files in the 'data' directory,
  processes user inputs (search, filters, booking, participant management), and renders HTML templates with data.

- templates/
  Directory containing all HTML template files for the web pages, each corresponding to one of the eight pages:
  - dashboard.html: Dashboard page layout and elements.
  - events_listing.html: Events catalog with search and filter UI.
  - event_details.html: Detailed event information and booking button.
  - ticket_booking.html: Ticket booking form and confirmation display.
  - participants_management.html: Participant list management interface.
  - venues.html: Venue listing and details.
  - event_schedules.html: Event schedules and timeline view.
  - bookings_summary.html: User bookings overview and cancellation.

- static/
  Contains static assets used by the web pages:
  - css/styles.css: Stylesheet for consistent styling across pages.
  - js/scripts.js: JavaScript for client-side interactivity (e.g., button actions, dynamic filtering).
  - images/: Folder for any images used in event or venue cards.

- data/
  Stores all application data in text files as specified:
  - events.txt: Event information.
  - venues.txt: Venue details.
  - tickets.txt: Ticket types and availability.
  - bookings.txt: User bookings data.
  - participants.txt: Participants and attendee information.
  - schedules.txt: Event session schedules.

This structure keeps the backend logic centralized in one Python file (app.py) for simplicity, while separating frontend templates and static resources for maintainability and clarity. The data directory holds all persistent data in text files as required.
